<subSubSection id="5AD5657B4F06303FFF64F8E3FCBCF810" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="127036F04F06303FFF64F8E3FCBCF810" blockId="21.[151,1436,1661,2010]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis id="20BBEAE24F06303FFF64F8E3FEBFF8EC" bold="true" box="[199,321,1805,1830]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Male: body uniformly light brown; frons subtriangular with tiny antero-median projection; punctures on head fine but distinct, clearly more distinct than those on pronotum; BL &lt;
<quantity id="D5379B154F06303FFB34F8DFFAFEF883" box="[1175,1280,1841,1866]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" unit="mm" value="0.6">0.60 mm</quantity>
; pronotum as broad as head, with ante-basal transverse groove; EI &lt;
<number id="A40724D74F06303FFCA6F8BBFCC7F8A4" box="[773,825,1877,1902]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="1.5">1.50</number>
; aedeagus with distinct internal armature containing a pair of lightly sclerotized strongly elongate sub-median sclerites surrounded at the level of basal foramen by a pair of darkly sclerotized loops and with subapical lateral groups of densely assembled microscopic needle-like structures. Females and their diagnostic characters unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5AD5657B4F05303CFF64FF79FE5CFC02" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="description">
<paragraph id="127036F04F05303CFF64FF79FEF5FF32" blockId="22.[151,1436,151,1149]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis id="20BBEAE24F05303CFF64FF79FEA7FF7A" bold="true" box="[199,345,151,176]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Description.</emphasis>
Body of male (
<figureCitation id="8AF42A754F05303CFDA9FF79FDA2FF7A" box="[522,604,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURES 20 – 28" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1586,1609]" captionTargetBox="[159,1435,210,1555]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,193,1565]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 20 – 28. Dorsal habitus of holotypes. Microscydmus (Scydmomicrus) australiensis Franz, female (20); M. (Sc.) nasicornis Franz, female (21); M. (Sc.) capitiseboraci sp. n., male (22); M. (Sc.) queenslandicus sp. n., male (23); M. (Sc.) styxianus sp. n., male (24); M. (Sc.) edithensis sp. n., male (25); M. (Sc.) tooloomensis sp. n., male (26); Penicillidmus masseyensis sp. n., male (27); P. unicolor sp. n., male (28)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285699/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
Fig. 
<number id="A40724D74F05303CFD9CFF76FDA2FF7A" box="[575,604,152,176]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" value="24.0">24</number>
</figureCitation>
) moderately convex, strongly elongate and slender, with moderately long appendages, BL 
<quantity id="D5379B154F05303CFEF7FF52FE34FF1E" box="[340,458,188,213]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.869999999999999" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" unit="mm" value="0.587">0.587 mm</quantity>
; cuticle glossy; body uniformly light brown with slightly lighter appendages; vestiture yellowish.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="127036F04F05303CFF64FEEAFC80FE67" blockId="22.[151,1436,151,1149]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
Head (
<figureCitation id="8AF42A754F05303CFEB7FEEAFE96FED6" box="[276,360,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURES 29 – 37" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1512,1535]" captionTargetBox="[157,1418,212,1473]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,193,1492]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 29 – 37. Body silhouette of holotypes. Microscydmus (Scydmomicrus) australiensis Franz, female (29); M. (Sc.) nasicornis Franz, female (30); M. (Sc.) capitiseboraci sp. n., male (31); M. (Sc.) queenslandicus sp. n., male (32); M. (Sc.) styxianus sp. n., male (33); M. (Sc.) edithensis sp. n., male (34); M. (Sc.) tooloomensis sp. n., male (35); Penicillidmus masseyensis sp. n., male (36); P. unicolor sp. n., male (37)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285700/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
Fig. 
<number id="A40724D74F05303CFEE8FEEAFE96FED6" box="[331,360,260,284]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" value="33.0">33</number>
</figureCitation>
) subtrapezoidal, broadest at eyes, HL 0.100 mm, HW 
<quantity id="D5379B154F05303CFC41FEEAFBA7FED6" box="[994,1113,260,285]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" unit="mm" value="0.15">0.150 mm</quantity>
; tempora much shorter than eyes, strongly convergent postero-mesally; vertex weakly convex; frons subtriangular with small antero-median projection. Eyes large but moderately projecting laterally from the head silhouette, coarsely faceted. Punctures on head dorsum sparse and small but distinct; setae short, sparse and suberect. Antennae slender, AnL 
<quantity id="D5379B154F05303CFABCFE81FA66FE4D" box="[1311,1432,367,392]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" unit="mm" value="0.25">0.250 mm</quantity>
; antennomeres I–II elongate, III–X transverse; XI as long as broad.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="127036F04F05303CFF64FE56FDC9FDF7" blockId="22.[151,1436,151,1149]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation id="8AF42A754F05303CFEE7FE59FE6BFE1A" box="[324,405,439,464]" captionStart="FIGURES 29 – 37" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1512,1535]" captionTargetBox="[157,1418,212,1473]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,193,1492]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 29 – 37. Body silhouette of holotypes. Microscydmus (Scydmomicrus) australiensis Franz, female (29); M. (Sc.) nasicornis Franz, female (30); M. (Sc.) capitiseboraci sp. n., male (31); M. (Sc.) queenslandicus sp. n., male (32); M. (Sc.) styxianus sp. n., male (33); M. (Sc.) edithensis sp. n., male (34); M. (Sc.) tooloomensis sp. n., male (35); Penicillidmus masseyensis sp. n., male (36); P. unicolor sp. n., male (37)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285700/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
Fig. 
<number id="A40724D74F05303CFEDBFE56FE6BFE1A" box="[376,405,440,464]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" value="33.0">33</number>
</figureCitation>
) in dorsal view oval, broadest near anterior third, PL 
<quantity id="D5379B154F05303CFC4BFE56FBA5FE05" box="[1000,1115,440,464]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.37" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" unit="mm" value="0.137">0.137 mm</quantity>
, PW 
<quantity id="D5379B154F05303CFB34FE59FAF5FE05" box="[1175,1291,439,464]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" unit="mm" value="0.15">0.150 mm</quantity>
; anterior and lateral margins rounded; posterior margin shallowly bisinuate; base of pronotum with two pairs of small and shallow pits, internal pair connected by transverse impression. Punctures on pronotal disc fine and inconspicuous; setae sparse, thin, short and suberect.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="127036F04F05303CFF64FDA9FDA3FD07" blockId="22.[151,1436,151,1149]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
Elytra oval, slightly more convex than pronotum, broadest near middle, EL 
<quantity id="D5379B154F05303CFB9DFDA9FB48FD95" box="[1086,1206,583,608]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" unit="mm" value="0.35">0.350 mm</quantity>
, EW 
<quantity id="D5379B154F05303CFB58FDA6FA8CFD95" box="[1275,1394,584,608]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.37" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" unit="mm" value="0.237">0.237 mm</quantity>
, EI 
<number id="A40724D74F05303CFF34FD82FF27FD4E" box="[151,217,620,644]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" value="1.474">1.474</number>
; basal impressions short; elytral apices separately rounded. Punctures on elytral disc slightly more distinct than those on pronotum but still fine and unremarkable; setae short, sparse and suberect. 
<collectingCountry id="6AD876604F05303CFB75FD61FAF0FD62" box="[1238,1294,655,680]" name="India" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Hind</collectingCountry>
wings well developed, about twice as long as elytra.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="127036F04F05303CFF64FD36FCB0FD3A" blockId="22.[151,1436,151,1149]" box="[199,846,727,752]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Legs moderately long and slender, without modifications.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="127036F04F05303CFF64FD12FF34FC6E" blockId="22.[151,1436,151,1149]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
Aedeagus (
<figureCitation id="8AF42A754F05303CFEE7FD12FE68FCDF" box="[324,406,764,789]" captionStart="FIGURES 54 – 61" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1561,1584]" captionTargetBox="[152,1427,213,1530]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[151,1436,193,1540]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 54 – 61. Aedeagi in ventral views. M. (Sc.) capitiseboraci sp. n. (54); M. (Sc.) queenslandicus sp. n. (55); M. (Sc.) styxianus sp. n. (56); M. (Sc.) edithensis sp. n. (57); M. (Sc.) tooloomensis sp. n. (58 – 59); Penicillidmus masseyensis sp. n. (60); P. unicolor sp. n. (61)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285705/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
Fig. 
<number id="A40724D74F05303CFEDAFD12FE68FCDF" box="[377,406,764,789]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" value="56.0">56</number>
</figureCitation>
) large, AeL 
<quantity id="D5379B154F05303CFD80FD12FD74FCDE" box="[547,650,764,788]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" unit="mm" value="0.13">0.13 mm</quantity>
; moderately slender, with distinct internal armature containing several well-defined components: a pair of lightly sclerotized strongly elongate sub-median sclerites extending from base to subapical region of median lobe, sub-basally located pair of dark lateral sclerites forming elongate loops, and subapical lateral groups of densely assembled microscopic needle-like structures; each paramere with long apical seta.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="127036F04F05303CFF64FC41FE5CFC02" blockId="22.[151,1436,151,1149]" box="[199,418,943,968]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis id="20BBEAE24F05303CFF64FC41FEE0FC02" bold="true" box="[199,286,943,968]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Female</emphasis>
. Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5AD5657B4F05303CFF64FC3AFC8FFC27" box="[199,881,980,1005]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="127036F04F05303CFF64FC3AFC8FFC27" blockId="22.[151,1436,151,1149]" box="[199,881,980,1005]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis id="20BBEAE24F05303CFF64FC3AFEA7FC27" bold="true" box="[199,345,980,1005]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Distribution</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="8AF42A754F05303CFECBFC3AFE42FC27" box="[360,444,980,1005]" captionStart="FIGURES 62 – 63" captionStartId="17.[151,264,1608,1631]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,1055,1586]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[151,1436,1055,1586]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 62 – 63. Distribution of Microscydmus (Scydmomicrus subgen. n.) (62) and Penicillidmus gen. n. (63). Microscydmus (Scydmomicrus) australiensis Franz (62 a); M. (Sc.) nasicornis Franz (62 b); M. (Sc.) capitiseboraci sp. n. (2 c); M. (Sc.) queenslandicus sp. n. (62 d); M. (Sc.) styxianus sp. n. (62 e); M. (Sc.) edithensis sp. n. (62 f); M. (Sc.) tooloomensis sp. n. (62 g); Microscydmus (Sc.) sp. (62 h); Penicillidmus masseyensis sp. n. (63 a); P. unicolor sp. n. (63 b); Penicillidmus sp. (63 c)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/285706/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
Fig. 
<number id="A40724D74F05303CFE3EFC3AFE42FC27" box="[413,444,980,1005]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" value="62.0">62</number>
</figureCitation>
e). E 
<collectingCountry id="6AD876604F05303CFE57FC3AFDA5FC27" box="[500,603,980,1005]" name="Australia" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Australia</collectingCountry>
(NE New South 
<collectingCountry id="6AD876604F05303CFCBFFC3AFC9BFC27" box="[796,869,980,1005]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Wales</collectingCountry>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5AD5657B4F05303CFF64FC19FB7BFBDA" box="[199,1157,1015,1040]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="127036F04F05303CFF64FC19FB7BFBDA" blockId="22.[151,1436,151,1149]" box="[199,1157,1015,1040]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis id="20BBEAE24F05303CFF64FC19FEB0FBDA" bold="true" box="[199,334,1015,1040]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Etymology.</emphasis>
Locotypical, after the Styx River, near which the 
<typeStatus id="CD7488524F05303CFCDFFC19FC20FBDA" box="[892,990,1015,1040]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">holotype</typeStatus>
was collected.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5AD5657B4F05303CFF64FBF2FD9EFBB7" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="127036F04F05303CFF64FBF2FD9EFBB7" blockId="22.[151,1436,151,1149]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis id="20BBEAE24F05303CFF64FBF2FEC5FBFF" bold="true" box="[199,315,1052,1077]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="D5CF4D734F05303CFEE7FBF2FDA6FBFE" box="[324,600,1052,1076]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Microscydmus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="styxianus">
<emphasis id="20BBEAE24F05303CFEE7FBF2FDA6FBFE" box="[324,600,1052,1076]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Microscydmus styxianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the most slender Australian species; it can be easily identified on the basis of the very short pronotum in relation to the elytra. The ratio EL/PL for 
<taxonomicName id="D5CF4D734F05303CFBB3FBAFFB61FB9D" box="[1040,1183,1088,1112]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Microscydmus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="styxianus">
<emphasis id="20BBEAE24F05303CFBB3FBAFFB61FB9D" box="[1040,1183,1088,1112]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">M. styxianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is 
<number id="A40724D74F05303CFB61FBD1FAFAFB92" box="[1218,1284,1087,1112]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" value="2.545">2.545</number>
, while for all remaining species it equals 
<number id="A40724D74F05303CFE6FFB8AFDA2FBB7" box="[460,604,1124,1149]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" value="2.1285" valueMax="2.4" valueMin="1.857">1.857–2.400</number>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
